<h1>Problem 969 - 2018 RMMSL, C1, CG</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 6</h2>
<p>Call a point in the Cartesian plane with integer coordinates a <i>lattice point</i>. Given a finite set \(\mathcal{S}\) of lattice points we repeatedly perform the following operation: given two distinct lattice points \(A, B\) in \(\mathcal{S}\) and two distinct lattice points \(C, D\) not in \(\mathcal{S}\) such that \(ACBD\) is a parallelogram with \(AB > CD\), we replace \(A, B\) by \(C, D\). Show that only finitely many such operations can be performed.</p>
